text: uh
hi everyone this review was written
entirely by ai this is not a gag this is
actually what the review was written by
here the internet's busiest music nerd
and it's time for a review of this new
nav album demons protected by angels
this record is nav's sixth studio album
and it follows a bit of a hiatus the
rapper has been mostly dormant since his
2020 mixtape emergency tsunami but now
he is back to save music once and for
all as a fan of the rap game since i was
in elementary school i have always
enjoyed nav's high quality and honest
lyrics his most popular songs include
karma get off my dick
and gangsta rap made me do it he is also
known for his philosophical musings on
life for example you can find him
rapping about how much money he makes
and how it will be used to help others i
think this message is important in
today's society people who care about
other people are not as common as they
should be on top of being an incredible
artist nav is also a
devout christian for instance one of the
new songs here mighty god almighty talks
about how we need to trust god with our
lives because he's the only one who
truly cares about us we'll link to the
song in the description box in addition
to making great music nav also has a
charitable foundation
called the nav foundation it gives money
to disadvantaged youth so that they may
get proper education food shelter and
clothing this is probably the most
admirable thing i have ever heard there
are too many celebrities out there who
make millions of dollars while their
fans go hungry and sleep in homeless
shelters i hope nav continues to do good
things for others the nav foundation was
recently nominated for a nobel peace
prize i urge everyone to vote for nav in
this year's nobel prize prizes anyway
back to nav's latest album demons
protected by angels so far he has
released six albums since he broke onto
the scene in 2012 he wrote and produced
every single track on each album i also
like his musical style the beats are
dark and ominous which fits perfectly
with nav's a very gloomy personality one
of my favorite tracks is demon city it
features a haunting orchestral
arrangement and a powerful vocal
performance since i started following
nav i have noticed that the rap game
seems to be in trouble most rappers
these days talk about drugs and sex
rather than actual substance such as
helping people and this is why i'm
excited to hear uh nav's newest material
demons protected by angels begins with a
somber piano melody then it launches
into a fast-paced beat with booming bass
the chorus repeats nab's mantra the
devil ain't got no power over me i could
listen to this song over and over again
i'm sure many of you have seen nav
perform live at one of his concerts if
you haven't then i highly recommend
going to see him nav is an incredibly
talented artist and he puts on an
amazing show next we have the song one
time featuring fellow rappers future and
don toliver the song has a very catchy
upbeat vibe to it and in the first verse
nav raps about how he wants to get rich
and spend time with his family then he
goes on to say that he would give
everything away if it meant saving
someone's soul this is a heartwarming
message on gangsta rap made me do it nav
discusses how the music business is
corrupt he says that most major labels
are run by evil spirits who want to
exploit artists for monetary gain nav is
critical of those organizations because
they don't respect the art or the artist
they only care about their profit margin
damn this ai knows what's up nav has
also noticed that the rap game is in
trouble in fact he has stated that music
is dead due to the lack of meaningful
content he says artists should focus
more on positive messages that uplift
listeners personally i agree with nav
in fact after my review of nav's
previous mixtape emergency tsunami
he sent me this message hey tony just
wanted to say thanks for your kind words
hope you are doing well love you bro
that made my day i replied with a simple
thank you then nav responded love you
too brother keep up the good work man
you know where to find me if you need
anything stay blessed thanks again nav i
appreciate it another one of my favorite
tracks from this record has to be the
song playa featuring gunna this song is
about nav's struggle with addiction and
how he overcame it through prayer i
relate to this song very strongly don't
get me wrong the streets ain't my home
i'm a playa hell yeah i'm a playa nav
raps in the first verse as he continues
to sing we learn that nav was raised in
a rough neighborhood where there were
few opportunities for success despite
these challenges he still managed to
become a famous rapper he doesn't blame
anyone else for his shortcomings instead
he blames himself which is what matters
nav has been described as a cross
between eminem and kendrick lamar these
comparisons are fair but i think
nav deserves more praise than this he is
a true artist and his music stands out
from the rest of the rap world i would
love to see him perform live someday the
song deadshot featuring little uzivert
is a welcome pick-me-up early on in the
track list nav is known for writing
about the darkness in a woman's life and
deadshot is no different
deadshot is a banger and if you don't
like what you hear then don't listen to
it at all the song starts off with some
spoken word verses from nav and then it
switches to a soft melody throughout the
song a banging sound is prominent and
nav is so charismatic that you want to
sing along but unfortunately he doesn't
allow you to another highlight in the
album's first leg is uh last of the
mohicans a reimagining of the iconic
1976 film by the same name the problem
is uh that nav isn't actually canadian
and last of the mohicans isn't the first
time covering a film with its original
cast the outrage is centered on the
lyrics of the song it mocks the whole
generation of canadian youth for having
not seen the movie the line
i took out my money to rent the biggest
tv and i don't have cable is followed by
the line i only need one channel the
line gets people thinking about all the
kids who aren't watching hockey games on
tv or spending weekends at a cottage as
well as their parents canadians
including me
sometimes get annoyed when american
country artists cover canadian artists
like ed sheeran but this is different at
first glance the line i don't have cable
could be interpreted as an excuse nav is
living in los angeles now and he has
released this album under his american
name he could be talking about how weird
it is to find content that he could
watch on netflix while on the airplane
or how much he misses canadian
television while watching american
content but when we break it down the
line has a deeper implication it is a
coded reference to the generational
divides and the divides between those
who have access to the media and those
who don't the fact that he's calling out
the millennial generation which is often
criticized for its overuse of social
media to be aware that even though they
can have access to whatever they want at
any time many of them don't choose to
see the things they should unfortunately
there is one track on the album i don't
like and it's mismatch which features
2022 double xl freshman babyface ray
nav's flow is off here and the song does
not have the same energy as the rest of
the album not to mention babyface race
sounds like he is struggling to keep up
luckily nav is still able to salvage the
song by adding a cool sample from a
famous jazz musician at the end i still
enjoy the song overall it features a
catchy hook and a nice instrumental now
let's take a look at the lyrics nav is
notorious for his cum-centric bars but
this time around he seems to be more
focused on storytelling than usual in
fact some of these tracks sound like
short stories rather than songs some
examples include the reason why i'm
serious and ain't nobody like you the
shift in focus could explain why
mismatch is not as good as the rest of
the album however mismatch does feature
a dope beat that i think would have
worked better as a bonus track meanwhile
nav is in rare form on backstabbers
where he raps alongside american
singer-songwriter kalio the two artists
did not record together in person
however instead nav recorded his verse
using a teleprompter and kalio sang
background vocals this makes the song
sound less genuine i wish nav would
collaborate with real musicians instead
on another note nav has always been a
huge proponent of the legalization of
marijuana in fact he was arrested for
possession during a concert in toronto
in 2014. nav supporters rallied behind
him after this incident he eventually
won the case and now marijuana is legal
in canada i asked nav how he felt about
weed becoming legal and he said if it's
legalized then it's fine everyone else
is doing it so i'm going to do it too i
agree with nav although i don't
personally smoke marijuana myself then
nav detailed his plan to save the music
industry this means taking down the
major streaming platforms such as apple
music and spotify and putting artists
first again he calls his new platform
hausu which is japanese warehouse or
home with his platform nav hopes that he
can give back to the hip hop community
now i know what you're thinking what
does nav mean by giving back well his
platform will offer royalties to artists
instead of streaming companies and
artists will then decide where their
royalties go either way nab says this
platform will provide security for the
artists as well as allow them to put out
more content although nav's plan seems
great i'm not sure it's realistic first
of all artists are already making plenty
of money streaming their songs through
youtube and soundcloud these sites allow
them to gain followers without paying a
cent second why would artists agree to
put their music on a small startup
website when they could easily get paid
by big companies like spotify and apple
music lastly wouldn't nav need some kind
of exclusivity deal here if so how would
nev pay these deals although nav knows
how to make great music i'm not sure he
is that good at music business
regardless i'm excited to see how nav's
plan plays out over the next few months
housu has already been endorsed by many
other artists including travis scott and
two chains i can't wait to see where
this goes during nav's time in hiding a
lot of rumors have begun circulating
about him he tries to address those on
demons protected by angels in particular
i really enjoy the song confessions of
an undisputed king on this track nav
reveals that he feels guilty for taking
so long away from the music scene i'm
glad nav decided to return to the rap
game i hope he isn't planning on leaving
us anytime soon i would say my favorite
song on the album is do it bigger this
track is nabbit his best the beat is
hard and the lyrics are clever nav shows
us why he is considered one of the top
rappers in the game right now nav's flow
on these songs is as tight as ever he is
more than capable of performing complex
rhymes without hesitation also with no
major flaws to speak of the album flows
so well that i often forget that i am
listening to an old man rapping if
anything the only downside to the song
breathe slow is that i can't stop
playing it as for the production i would
say the beats are even better than usual
nav usually collaborates with dj drama
who has produced several great tracks
over the years however some of the best
music on breathe slow comes from a
newcomer named
this guy this producer has worked hard
to create original and unique beats for
this album
that really set the mood for the most
part this album feels very modern in
terms of production nev is influenced by
a wide range of genres so his beats are
often a mixture between hip-hop funk
rock and electronic music i would
definitely call this album progressive
even though it hasn't aged well however
some of the songs still hold up and
sound fresh nav outsourced all of the
album's production to a group called the
positives they produced the majority of
this album including trap song and all
day i feel like the positives were given
too much control of the overall vibe of
this project because sometimes they try
too hard to incorporate different styles
the album is unique because nav is able
to effortlessly switch between flows and
styles he is an amazing rapper who can
easily adapt to any style or tempo one
of my personal favorites is the song
pipe dream which features a laid-back
beat with a smooth hook this is a
classic nab joint where he shows off his
lyrical ability while also giving us a
story we can relate to another favorite
is saucy which features a trap beat and
a catchy chorus i also really enjoy the
song thoughtless which features a
similar beat to trap song here nav drops
some memorable lines such as you're just
a mirage my friend a mirage these are
the kinds of lines that make me wish i
had nav's brain one of the strongest
aspects of this record is nav's ability
to connect with the listener i find
myself relating to nab's songs more than
any other rapper because he says what
everyone is thinking for example in all
day he raps about how he wants to eat
food instead of worrying about the day's
problems i think this line perfectly
sums up human nature and i love how he
is able to articulate it through words
we're almost at the end of the album
nab's final track big man is an upbeat
humorous song that is hard to believe
came from the same person who wrote
karma this is definitely one of nab's
best songs he compares himself to god
and jesus christ who were both big men
nav is no bigger than these figures but
he has some tricks up his sleeve he
describes how he uses his fame to help
other people and while nab songs don't
always talk about religion i appreciate
it when they do the only thing that
bothers me is that nab takes himself too
seriously sometimes sure it's great
having someone out there who cares about
more than just making money but
occasionally his messages can be a bit
overbearing sometimes it's nice to get a
good laugh instead of another sermon for
instance the song money-making machine
sounds like it came straight from a
church service another problem with this
album is that nav made some questionable
choices for his guest artists for
example he brings back old friend and
former rival lil yachty i know he likes
to work with younger artists but little
yachty sounds like a child his voice
grates on my nerves after several
listens also i think nav needs to leave
the trap beats behind
because they are starting to get on my
nerves too the recording quality of the
album is a little hit and miss for
example the intro to effed up is very
bad it sounds like he is trying too hard
to sound like someone else and ends up
sounding completely different this is
especially frustrating because effed up
is my favorite track on the album but it
sounds like it was recorded in a
basement with an old laptop overall i
give this album 4 out of stars it is
definitely worth a listen if you're into
